{
  "answer": "**The passage appears in Charles Dunoyer's *Nouveau traité d'économie: VOL II*, chapter 16 (\"VI. De la liberté de l'industrie manufacturière\").**[^1]\n\nThis chapter contrasts French manufacturing, which focuses on luxury goods for elites (e.g., jewelry, fashion items, fine silks), with English manufacturing's emphasis on mass production of everyday necessities (e.g., iron, woolens, cottons, beer). The author argues that England's approach yields greater power and profits despite its smaller population, using the requested statistics as evidence.[^1]\n\nThe specific comparison is:  \n> A London brewer, M. Perkins, alone sells for nearly as much in beer as the three hundred and seventy-six butchers of Paris annually buy in meat at the markets of Sceaux and Poissy: while our butchers, according to the official statistics I have already cited, buy only 45 million worth of meat, the brewer of whom I speak sells 40 million worth of beer.[^1]\n\n[^1]: Charles Dunoyer, *Nouveau traité d'économie: VOL II*, [paragraph](/works/charles-dunoyer-nouveau-traite-deconomie-vol-ii-d6ae03/16-vi-de-la-liberte-de-lindustrie-manufacturiere/translation/#p-78e243).",
